Package gw.api.modules.rest.framework.v1.resources

Class RestElementResource

java.lang.Object
gw.api.modules.rest.framework.v1.resources.RestResource
gw.api.modules.rest.framework.v1.resources.RestElementResource
Direct Known Subclasses:
AsyncRequestPlatformResource, AsyncRequestResponsePlatformResource, CalendarDateCalculationPlatformResource, ClaimGraphSchemaCoreResource, DatabaseConsistencyCheckReportPlatformResource, DefaultRestElementResource, EntitySchemaPlatformResource, EntitySchemasPlatformResource, OpenApiJsonPlatformResource
public abstract class RestElementResource extends RestResource

Base class for all element resources. An element resource is a resource that represents a single element, as opposed to a collection of resources.

Element resources typically (though not always) are contained within a parent. Element resources with parents should not directly extend this class, but DefaultRestElementResource (or a subclass thereof) instead.

Element resources that do not have parents are root resources, and can extend this class directly.

      public RestRequestException getCanEditException()
      This method can be overridden to handle cases where the user is permitted to edit this resource, but the resource cannot be edited for some other reason related to the object's state. Return null to indicate that resource can be edited provided the caller has permission, and return a RestRequestException to indicate that the resource cannot be edited for some other reason.

    • getCanonicalId

      public String getCanonicalId()
      Returns the "canonical" id of this element, used for de-duplicating and merging included resources in cases where the same RestElementResource is loaded from multiple different inclusion paths. Generally this is going to be the RestId of the underlying entity, but it may also be some other unique identifier, such as a unique Code.

    • validateBeforeCommit

      public void validateBeforeCommit()
      Final validation before commit, to check for invariants that cannot easily be validated on a per-request basis because they require checks that cross individual resource boundaries. This method will always be called after finishCreate or finishPatch, and will be called for custom actions as well as POST and PATCH requests, but not for DELETE requests. The exact lifecycle of when this method is called depends on the context in which this resource is used:
      • In an individual REST request, validation will happen after finishCreate or finishPatch
      • When using request inclusion, validation will happen after all included resources are fully processed
      • Within a Composite API request, validation will happen after all sub-requests have been processed
      • Within a Graph API request, validation will happen after the entire graph has been processed
      Failures here should throw RestRequestExceptions.

    • getProcessingOrder

      public int getProcessingOrder()
      This property can be used to determine the order in which this element is processed relative to other elements included in the same request. In general, order should be insignicant when processing entities, but this allows for some measure of control for the hopefully-rare cases where order does in fact matter. Lower numbers will be processed first, with a default order of 0.
